nctions must use a unique combination of allowed numpy operations.\n\nLet me start by understanding the problem. The priority function assigns a score to each bin, and the bin with the highest score is chosen for the next item. Common heuristics like Best Fit or First Fit use such priority functions.\n\nI'll think of different ways to compute the priority score. Each function should combine different operations to ensure uniqueness.\n\n1. **First Function**: Maybe use the remaining capacity of each bin. The remaining capacity is (bin size - sum of items in bin). So, for each bin, calculate how much space is left. Then, apply an exponential function to this value to get the priority. So, priority = exp(remaining_capacity).\n\nBut wait, the bins array represents the current size of each bin. So, the remaining capacity is (bin_size - bins[i]). Assuming bin_size is a constant, but I don't have that info. Hmm, maybe the bins array is the sum of items in each bin, and each bin has a fixed size, say 1.0. Or perhaps the bins are of variable sizes? The problem statement isn't clear. Wait, the function signature is def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray. So, bins is an array where each element represents the current size of the bin. The item is the size of the new item to pack.\n\nSo, the remaining capacity of each bin is (bins[i] + item) <= bin capacity. Wait, no. Each bin has a maximum capacity, which I think is the same for all bins, perhaps 1.0. Or maybe each bin can have varying capacities. The problem statement doesn't specify. I think in bin packing, bins are usually of the same capacity. So, perhaps each bin has a fixed capacity, say 1.0, and the bins array represents the sum of items in each bin so far.\n\nSo, for a bin with current sum 'b', the remaining capacity is (1.0 - b). But the function doesn't have the bin capacity as an argument. Hmm, this complicates things. Maybe the bins array can accept the new item if b + item <= 1.0.\n\nBut in the function, I don't have access to the bin capacity. So perhaps the priority is based on how much space is left in each bin relative to the item size.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps the bins are allowed to have varying capacities, but I think in standard bin packing, bins are uniform. So, I'll proceed under the assumption that each bin has a capacity of 1.0.\n\nSo, the remaining capacity for each bin is (1.0 - bins[i]). The priority could be based on this.\n\nBut how to compute the priority. For example, in Best Fit, the priority is the smallest remaining space that is >= item. But the function needs to return a score for each bin, which is then used to select the bin with the highest score.\n\nSo, for each bin, the priority could be a combination of how much space is left, how well it fits the item, and perhaps other factors like the bin's current load.\n\nLet me think of different ways to combine these factors.\n\nFunction 1: Use the remaining capacity (1.0 - bins[i]) and apply an exponential function. So, priority = exp(remaining_capacity). But this would prioritize bins with more space. However, we also need to ensure that the bin can fit the item. So, perhaps the priority is exp((remaining_capacity - item)/remaining_capacity) or something similar.\n\nWait, but the function needs to return a score for each bin, regardless of whether it can fit the item. The selection process will choose the bin with the highest score that can fit the item.\n\nSo, the priority function can be any function, and the selection is done by choosing the highest priority bin that can accommodate the item.\n\nSo, the functions don't need to check if the bin can fit the item; that's handled elsewhere.\n\nSo, I can focus on creating scores based on various features.\n\nLet me think of different features:\n\n- Remaining capacity: (1.0 - bins[i])\n- How well the remaining capacity matches the item: |remaining_capacity - item|\n- The bin's current load: bins[i]\n- The ratio of item to remaining capac