p.ndarray:\n    return np.where(bins >= item, 1, 0)\n```\n\n### Implementation 4: Variance Minimization\nPlaces the item to minimize the variance in bin usage.\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    current_var = np.var(bins)\n    new_var = np.var(np.where(bins >= item, bins - item, bins))\n    return np.where(bins >= item, new_var, np.inf)\n```\n\n### Implementation 5: Use Smaller Bins First\nPrefers smaller bins to save larger ones for larger items.\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.where(bins <= item, bins, np.inf)\n```\n\n### Implementation 6: Maximize Remaining Space\nPlaces the item in a bin that leaves the most space.\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    fit = bins >= item\n    remaining = np.where(fit, bins - item, 0)\n    return remaining\n```\n\n### Implementation 7: Use Bins with Similar Sizes\nChooses bins closest in size to the item.\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    diff = np.abs(bins - item)\n    return 1 / (diff + 1e-9)\n```\n\n### Implementation 8: Avoid Empty Bins\nFills empty bins first.\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.where(bins == 0, 1, 0)\n```\n\n### Implementation 9: Use Bins with Most Space Left\nPrioritizes bins with the most remaining capacity.\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    available = bins\n    return available\n```\n\n### Implementation 10: Minimize Fragmentation\nReduces bin space fragmentation by placing the item in the first suitable bin.\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    fit = bins >= item\n    return np.where(fit, np.cumsum(fit), 0)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.sqrt(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, 