lize or reward bin sizes.\n2. Combining logarithmic functions to handle different scales.\n3. Using trigonometric functions to create oscillating penalties.\n4. Incorporating statistical measures like mean and standard deviation.\n5. Applying different transformations, like adding or multiplying factors.\n\nI'll make sure each function uses a unique combination. For example, some might use np.exp combined with np.mean, others might use np.log and np.sin, etc.\n\nLet me draft each function step by step, ensuring they are different in structure and operations.\n\nFunction 1:\nUse exponential of (item - bin) multiplied by the item and the mean of bins. Add sine of pi times (item / bin) multiplied by 5. Add cosine of pi times (item + bin) multiplied by 2.\n\nWait, but looking at the examples, some have similar structures. I need to vary the operations and functions used.\n\nFunction 2:\nMaybe use the mean of bins multiplied by exponential of (item - bin), then add sine of (item / bin) and log(item + 1).\n\nFunction 3:\nLog(item +1) plus sine of (item / bin) plus mean of bins times exponential of (item - bin).\n\nHmm, but these are similar to the examples. I need to come up with new combinations.\n\nFunction 4:\nPerhaps use exp(item) multiplied by mean of bins, plus log(item +1), plus sine(pi*(item / bins)).\n\nWait, but in the examples, some have similar structures. Maybe vary the constants and the order of operations.\n\nFunction 5:\nUse exponential of (item - bin) multiplied by (item * std(bins)), plus sine of (item / bin) multiplied by 5, plus cosine of (item + bin) multiplied by 2.\n\nWait, this is similar to Example 1. I need to change it.\n\nLet me think differently. Maybe combine multiple functions in a different way. For example, using exp, log, and std in various combinations.\n\nFunction 6:\nCalculate the difference between item and each bin, take the exponential, multiply by the standard deviation of bins. Then add the log of (item + 1) and the sine of (item 